### INSTRUCTIONS: How to run these tests
# 1. Start the local DMS/CMS environment as described in `eng/docker-compose` (see `openiddict-demonstration.http` for example start steps).
# 2. Ensure the Configuration Service (CMS) is running and reachable at the `configPort` below (default 8081).
# 3. Use the VS Code REST Client extension to run the requests below in order. Responses are captured into variables for chained requests.

@configPort=8081

@sysAdminId=DmsConfigurationService
@sysAdminSecret=ValidClientSecret1234567890!Abcd

### Create a Configuration Service token (client credentials)
# @name configTokenRequest
POST http://localhost:{{configPort}}/connect/token
Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded

client_id={{sysAdminId}}
&client_secret={{sysAdminSecret}}
&grant_type=client_credentials
&scope=edfi_admin_api/full_access

### Read the token from the response body
@configToken={{configTokenRequest.response.body.access_token}}

### 1) GET list: /v2/resourceClaims (default list)
# Expected: 200 OK, returns top-level root nodes (with nested `children`)
GET http://localhost:{{configPort}}/v2/resourceClaims
Authorization: bearer {{configToken}}

### Capture first resource claim id and name for subsequent tests
@firstResourceClaimId=7
#{{response.body[0].id}}
@firstResourceClaimName=assessmentMetadata
#{{response.body[0].name}}

### 2) GET single item by id: /v2/resourceClaims/{id}
# Expected: 200 OK with full recursive subtree when found
GET http://localhost:{{configPort}}/v2/resourceClaims/{{firstResourceClaimId}}
Authorization: bearer {{configToken}}

### 3) GET list with paging, sorting and direction
GET http://localhost:{{configPort}}/v2/resourceClaims?limit=5&offset=0&orderBy=name&direction=asc
Authorization: bearer {{configToken}}

### 4) GET list filtering by name (case-insensitive)
GET http://localhost:{{configPort}}/v2/resourceClaims?name={{firstResourceClaimName}}
Authorization: bearer {{configToken}}

### 5) GET resourceClaimActions (flat list)
# Expected: 200 OK array of items with resourceClaimId, resourceName, claimName, actions
GET http://localhost:{{configPort}}/v2/resourceClaimActions
Authorization: bearer {{configToken}}

### 6) GET resourceClaimActions filtered by resourceName
GET http://localhost:{{configPort}}/v2/resourceClaimActions?resourceName={{firstResourceClaimName}}
Authorization: bearer {{configToken}}

### 7) GET resourceClaimActionAuthStrategies (flat list)
# Expected: 200 OK array with authorizationStrategiesForActions resolved
GET http://localhost:{{configPort}}/v2/resourceClaimActionAuthStrategies
Authorization: bearer {{configToken}}

### 8) GET resourceClaimActionAuthStrategies filtered by resourceName
GET http://localhost:{{configPort}}/v2/resourceClaimActionAuthStrategies?resourceName={{firstResourceClaimName}}
Authorization: bearer {{configToken}}

### 9) Validation test: unsupported orderBy should return 400 Bad Request
GET http://localhost:{{configPort}}/v2/resourceClaims?orderBy=unsupportedField
Authorization: bearer {{configToken}}

### Notes
- The spike defines strict failure modes: missing hierarchy metadata or unresolved lookups must produce server failures (see reference/spikes/DMS-1082/ticket-resource-claims-endpoints.md).
- These requests exercise basic success and validation behavior; add targeted negative tests (missing metadata) in unit/integration suites as needed.
